In article <16C14142E3.C445585@mizzou1.missouri.edu> C445585@mizzou1.missouri.edu (John Kelsey) writes:
> Secret key is x, public key is g**x mod p, g and p can be known by everyone.
> To sign a message, I find the hash h of my message.  Then, I calculate Z to
> satisfy Z * h = x (modulo (p-1)).  The signature of the message is then
> (h, g ** Z).  To verify the signature, a user simply verifies that
> (g ** Z) ** h = (g ** x) (modulo p).

To forge the signature of a message, I find its hash h. Then I calculate 
Y to satisfy Yh = 1 (mod p-1). Now g^(Yh) = g so g^(xYh) = g^x (mod p).
Hence (h, g^(xY)) is a valid signature, and I can calculate g^(xY) as
(g^x)^Y.

---Dan
